  "prompt": "Why all planets are circling the sun in the same direction?",
  "response": "All planets in the solar system orbit the Sun in the same direction because they formed from a rotating disk of gas and dust called the solar nebula. Here's a brief overview of the process:\n\n1. **Solar Nebula**: Around 4.6 billion years ago, the solar system began as a large cloud of gas and dust. This cloud collapsed under its own gravity, possibly triggered by shock waves from nearby supernovae.\n\n2. **Conservation of Angular Momentum**: As the cloud collapsed, it began to spin faster due to the conservation of angular momentum. The material in the cloud started to flatten and form a rotating disk.\n\n3. **Protoplanetary Disk**: Most of the mass concentrated in the center, forming the Sun, while the remaining material in the disk began to cool and coalesce into smaller bodies, eventually leading to the formation of planets.\n\n4. **Orbital Direction**: Because the entire disk was rotating in a consistent direction, the planets that formed within it naturally inherited this direction of movement. Thus, they all orbit the Sun in the same counterclockwise direction (when viewed from above the Sun's north pole).\n\n5. **Uniformity**: This directionality is consistent among the majority of objects in the solar system, including asteroids and comets, because they all originated from the same rotating nebula.\n\nIn summary, the shared direction of the planets' orbits around the Sun is a result of the physical conditions and processes that governed their formation from a rotating accretion disk.",
